FAQ – Aspireship About FAQ For Candidates For Employers Blog Pricing For Companies Sign in Sign Up FAQ Most frequent questions and answers What s an "Aspireship"? An Aspireship is a new kind of online training program designed as a bridge to advance you to a new step in your Whether you’re just starting your career, looking to level up to a more senior position or are wanting to make a move from another industry or job type, an Aspireship can help you get What Aspireships are available now? The SaaS Account Executive Aspireship is our first program designed to teach you how to become a “full cycle” Account Executive at a SaaS company (and most importantly, succeed once you land the job!). We’ll be adding more Aspireships soon! How does an Aspireship work? Aspireships are % online training programs, taught by current and former Founders, CEOs, VPs, Directors and training experts at SaaS Our curriculum is broken down into three main areas: Live and expert video interviews Quizzes and Assessments Virtual Job Simulations The curriculum can be completed , on your Once you fully complete the program, our team will review your assessment to determine if you have scored high enough to become certified and added to the Aspireship Talent Network to be discovered by Aspireship’s hiring How long does an Aspireship take to complete? The SaaS Account Executive Aspireship takes most candidates around hours of dedicated time to Candidates who study 5 hours week can usually finish in How much does an Aspireship cost? Aspireship is % tuition free for Candidates have the option to take advantage of Aspireship Pro to extend access beyond the limit, participate in live classes and Learn more about pricing here . Does Aspireship take a percentage of my income when I land a job? We don’t believe in taking a percentage of your Is there an application process to get in? Aspireship is accessible to anyone who wants to sign up, as we believe in providing opportunity to as many people as However, your performance throughout the Aspireship program is essentially your application to become certified and be admitted into the Aspireship Talent Am I guaranteed a job at the end of the program? Success in life is never At the end of your Aspireship, you’ll complete a graded assessment to determine if you score high enough to become certified and admitted to the Aspireship Talent Is there continuing education available after I complete the program? Should you choose to participate, you have the option to sign up for Aspireship Pro, a paid subscription offering that provides access to weekly live classes, an expanded video library and What if I don t want a job, but I do want to learn? Anyone is welcome to take the Aspireship program, participate in live classes and other learning opportunities through Aspireship We consistently hear from current SaaS AEs that Aspireship has been very helpful and we welcome their participation in the Does Aspireship offer access to companies? Learn more about Aspireship for Companies here . Why do you offer free day access? We believe in providing opportunity to anyone who is willing to put in the work, regardless of their ability to How do we make this work? Well, we work really hard to make it happen! We make money to support the growth of the business through premium subscriptions, certifications and job © Aspireship All rights   Pricing Information - Aspireship About FAQ For Candidates For Employers Blog Pricing For Companies Sign in Sign Up Get Unlimited Access Free for Days Become a pro member for ongoing access for just $29 month or $180 per GET STARTED NOW Unlimited Access Get unlimited access to Aspireship course curriculum and LIVE CLASSES Access live classes to interact with experts and get your questions answered​. Video LIBRARY Access our expanded collection of interviews with industry COMMUNITY Connect with other members to collaborate, share resources, and What s included in my trial? You’ll get unlimited access to the Aspireship SaaS sales curriculum, live classes, expanded video library and SaaS sales assessment for What s not included in my trial? Trial members can access everything in the Aspireship platform with the exception of our member community on slack, which requires a paid account for What happens after my trial expires? After days, you will no longer have access to the SaaS sales curriculum, live classes, expanded video library or the SaaS sales At any time before or after the trial period expires, you may upgrade to a pro subscription to gain ongoing Can I get certified without becoming a pro member? Trial members are free to complete the SaaS sales curriculum and final assessment during the trial A pro membership is not required to become certified or participate in the Aspireship Talent What does it cost to purchase a verifiable certificate? For candidates who score high enough on the final assessment to become certified, we offer the option to purchase a verifiable certificate

VitalGuides - Vitalxchange About Us For Professionals For VitalGuides Our Blog Menu About Us For Professionals For VitalGuides Our Blog VitalGuides Meet Our VitalGuides “If my experiences can be the guidebook for another family in similar situation, it would make it all worthwhile” Become a VitalGuide Who is a VitalGuide? A person who has a great deal of experience caring for a health condition or disability and wants to help others going through a similar Why are VitalGuides essential to the Vitalxchange community? VitalGuides provide guidance on how to handle challenges and other aspects of life based on their own They are relentless and resourceful in finding solutions that And most importantly, they are selfless and make it their life’s mission to help VitalGuides are a critical part of Not only do they provide our community guidance to navigate through life’s health challenges, they support us every step of the way, so we will never feel alone Become a VitalGuide Why should you become a VitalGuide? Convert goodwill into fair We know that you are used to helping people But we also know that you have made many sacrifices in your In return for your selfless commitment to help others in our community, we have created opportunities for you to make a fair fee for your Create and nurture your You can create private groups to share your support and Your members can engage with you 1:1 via virtual coffee chats or signup for other guidance services you want to You can help people remotely and collect payment all in one Help people all over the world Be part of the movement to increase global healthcare Your virtual services on Vitalxchange will reach millions all over the world in due time, especially those emerging parts of the world, where resources are still Hear from our VitalGuides Jennifer Rainey Jennifer is a parent expert who offers support through her Storefront on Vitalxchange called Autism’tude. We know from experience that social networks like facebook are not best places to have private conversations about one’s health or a child’s We also know that the algorithms that promote facebook’s are at odds with what many health influencers want to is why we created the Vitalxchange community and the VitalGuide program to make it tailored for health At Vitalxchange we connect you to people looking for your guidance and provide you the tools to make fair profit right from the start, because we want you to focus on what you do best – helping other How long does it take to get listed on Vitalxchange? Making smart contracts developer friendly - Second State Start coding Making smart contracts developer friendly Developing smart contracts and decentralized apps (dapps) is arduous Second State provides an open source stack of tools and runtime environments to make dapp development Getting started Learn about EVM and Ewasm Award from Ethereum Foundation Twin challenges of smart contract development Generic programming language Solidity, Vyper, and other smart contract languages are Turing complete generic programming They are not optimized for any specific application It is difficult to write or use application libraries in those The “world computer” is good for no particular The lowest common denominator The VM mixes consensus and Query view functions, which account for % of the usage, must adhere to the strict limitations required by the small number of transactional The smart contract is constrained by the lowest common denominator of consensus (e.g., no random number, very limited string function, no JSON). Etheruem solutions Generic programming language not optimized for any use case Solution Language (DSL) extensions to A good example is the Lity Rules Language for Solidity . Smart contracts are Incorporating formal and verifiable rules inside smart contracts is an important domain specific use See our video demo at Devcon5 . The lowest common denominator functions are needlessly constrained Solution Use an external ElasticSearch engine to support functions in auxiliary The example we demonstrated is the smart contract search engine . It provides information about states inside smart The JavaScript API gives dapps immediate and rich access to blockchain data without going through See an example dapp built on Ethereum solutions LLVM LLVM is the most widely used and optimized compiler toolchain for almost all modern computer Second State is leading the initiative to bring the LLVM into the Ethereum Read our collaboration statement with Ethereuem Classic on tool chain for At Devcon5, we demonstrated the world s first Solidty LLVM compiler that can run ERC20 contracts on Ethereum Foundation s Ewasm See the demo video here . Ewasm WebAssembly (WASM) is a highly optimized virtual The Ethereum flavored WebAssembly (Ewasm) is the smart contract execution environment for Ethereum and Together with the LLVM, it could potentially support all popular programming languages, including DSLs, on the frontend, and support many libraries for The Second State SOLL compiler can already generate smart contracts for Putting all together The Second State BUIDL IDE already supports domain specific language extensions, auxiliary application support, and will soon support LLVM Ewasm! Settings | Pomerium Pomerium Documentation Configuration Recipes Enterprise 🚧Dev GitHub Documentation Configuration Recipes Enterprise 🚧Dev GitHub Configuration Settings Shared Settings Authenticate Service Proxy Service Cache Service Policy Authorize Service Examples # Configuration Settings Pomerium can be configured using a configuration file ( YAML JSON TOML ) or environmental variables . In general, environmental variable keys are identical to config file keys but are in If you are coming from a kubernetes or docker background this should feel If not, check out the following Store config in the environment Kubernetes: Environment variables Kubernetes: Config Maps Docker: Environment variables Using both environmental variables and config file keys is allowed and encouraged (for instance, secret keys are probably best set as environmental variables). However, if duplicate configuration keys are found, environment variables take Pomerium will automatically reload the configuration file if it is At this time, only policy is when this reload occurs, but additional options may be added in the It is suggested that your policy is stored in a configuration file so that you can take advantage of this # Shared Settings These are configuration variables shared by all services, in all service # Service Mode Environmental Variable: SERVICES Config File Key: services Type: string Default: all Options: all authenticate authorize cache or proxy Service mode sets the pomerium service(s) to If testing, you may want to set to all and run pomerium in "all-in-one " In production, you ll likely want to spin up several instances of each service mode for high # Address Environmental Variable: ADDRESS Config File Key: address Type: string Example: :443 , :8443 Default: :443 Required Address specifies the host and port to serve HTTP requests If empty, :443 is Note, in deployments, gRPC traffic will be served on loopback on port :5443 . # Administrators Environmental Variable: ADMINISTRATORS Config File Key: administrators Type: slice of string Example: "admin@example.com " Administrative users are super user that can sign in as another user or User impersonation allows administrators to temporarily impersonate a different # Shared Secret Environmental Variable: SHARED_SECRET Config File Key: shared_secret Type: base64 encoded string Required Shared Secret is the base64 encoded key used to mutually authenticate requests between It s critical that secret keys are random, and stored Use a key management system or dev urandom to generate a For example: head dev urandom | base64 # Debug Environmental Variable: POMERIUM_DEBUG Config File Key: pomerium_debug Type: bool Default: false WARNING Enabling the debug flag will result in sensitive information being logged!!! By default, JSON encoded logs are Debug enables colored, logs to be streamed to standard out . In production, it s recommended to be set to false . For example, if true :37AM INF cmd pomerium version=v0.0.1-dirty+ede4124 :37AM INF proxy: new route from=httpbin.corp.beyondperimeter.com to=https: httpbin.org :37AM INF proxy: new route from=ssl.corp.beyondperimeter.com to=http: neverssl.com :37AM INF proxy authenticator: grpc connection OverrideCertificateName= addr=auth.corp.beyondperimeter.com:443 If false "level":"info","version":"v0.0.1-dirty+ede4124","time":"2019-02-18T10:41 :00","message":"cmd pomerium" "level":"info","from":"httpbin.corp.beyondperimeter.com","to":"https: httpbin.org","time":"2019-02-18T10:41 :00","message":"proxy: new route" "level":"info","from":"ssl.corp.beyondperimeter.com","to":"http: neverssl.com","time":"2019-02-18T10:41 :00","message":"proxy: new route" "level":"info","OverrideCertificateName":"","addr":"auth.corp.beyondperimeter.com:443","time":"2019-02-18T10:41 :00","message":"proxy authenticator: grpc connection" # Log Level Environmental Variable: LOG_LEVEL Config File Key: log_level Type: string Options: debug info warn error Default: debug Log level sets the global logging level for Only logs of the desired level and above will be # Insecure Server Environmental Variable: INSECURE_SERVER Config File Key: insecure_server Type: bool Required if certificates unset Turning on insecure server mode will result in pomerium starting, and operating without any protocol encryption in This setting can be useful in a situation where you have Pomerium behind a TLS terminating ingress or However, even in that case, it is highly recommended to use TLS to protect the confidentiality and integrity of service communication even behind the ingress using certificates or an internal Please see our for an example of just WARNING Pomerium should never be exposed to the internet without TLS # Certificate Environmental Variable: either CERTIFICATE or CERTIFICATE_FILE Config File Key: certificate or certificate_file Type: base64 encoded string or relative file location Required Certificate is the x509 used to establish secure HTTP and gRPC # Certificate Key Envir

The Browser Company Contact Jobs Twitter Thanks! This is a web It’s just a frame, with some buttons and It’s our window to everything on the We love the internet, but it can be What if a browser could help us make sense of it all? Could a browser keep us focused, organized and in control? At the Browser Company , we’re building a better way to use the When we think about browsing the internet, we often ignore the browser Instead, we think about all the things we do online—the articles we read, the emails we send, the shows we The software that enables it all, the browser, is so ubiquitous that it’s Despite the ways our internet use has evolved, the browser has remained relatively While all of our other software tools are changing for the better—with more collaborative features, flexible interfaces, and powerful functionality—the browser largely still does what it did years What’s more, we blame ourselves for the browser s When our browser has an overwhelming number of tabs, we call ourselves inefficient when we get distracted online, we tell ourselves we need more discipline when we can’t find a url, we think we re Why does the browser get a free pass? That’s why we re building a new browser—we believe it could do so much more to empower We’re imagining a browser that can think as quickly as we do, take work off of our plates, and pull our creativity A browser equipped for the way we use the internet in , and foundational for how we hope to use it in the Our Team Adena Hursh Josh Nate Samir +1 Senior Front End +1 Chromium +1 Senior Generalist +1 Product Designer The five of us learned a lot from working at a handful of startups, as well as Snap, Instagram, Facebook, Amazon, and the Obama White But we don t know everything, and have a ton to Which is to say, we re eager to work with creative, kind, and passionate Especially those from diverse If all of this aligns with your values, and one of our open roles feels like it may be a fit, please say hi . Support Beyond our team, we’re lucky to be supported by our family and friends, as well as investors who played a role in some of our favorite software companies over the years (Airtable, DuckDuckGo, Github, Instagram, Slack, Stripe). While we have the financial resources to sprint at our ambitions, we’re always grateful for new perspectives and shared learnings from If you’d like to lend a hand, please send us a note . Otherwise, feel free to join our friends and family newsletter , and we promise you’ll be among the first to play with our new Thanks!

Posted on April 5, April 5, by Rocky Here are five keys to success in security operations as they were derived from my interviews with SOC team leaders over the last few While this isn’t intended to be an document, I do believe it is a solid foundation for a healthy cyber defense Bonus: I’ve also listed are some of the major pitfalls that have led many organizations down a very sad and even more costly path in the hopes that others may avoid these altogether and instead focus on the strengths identified here or in the comments and conversations that this article Key Takeaway: “Healthy and maturing SOC teams relentlessly drive towards defined ” First Five “Keys” to Success: The Hire the best, then focus on growing the Invest in people over everything The right people can help you overcome flaws in technology and process if they are properly It takes talent to both attract and retain talent so don’t skimp Don’t be afraid of remote workers, with the right goals it’s very clear how everyone adds When building your team remember that diversity is key here as Hire people that ask questions by You’d be amazed by the team you can build around school teachers and police officers inquisitive and creative people can learn technology and push us to ask better questions about why we do things this We need innovative approaches, better questions, and creative It’s time to branch out past the people we know from previous lives and time to start creating the next generation to push us forw ard! Lesson learned: Having at least 3 stars on your team can help drive the right organizational dynamics and push the team across the board to be better, more collaborative and competitive in healthy Having one or two “stars” tends to drive a more negative sentiment sometimes moving towards dysfunction, whereas three or more seems to drive maturity and more healthy conversations in every Last note: Get used to remote teams, learn to manage them by having the right goals in Automate away the If it can be automated, then do If it is repeated on a daily basis, then automate If analysts are inconsistent in their delivery, then If analysts hate it, automate Basically, there is no reason for repetitive or work in the If you find yourself wanting to hire a junior person to do the tedious work – Automate SOAR can be your friend So can DevOps or any number of other tools and Lesson Learned: Technical solutions exist in many forms, but the path to success is likely not going to be adding layers of people to do the work of Having solid processed defined is the key to Let computers do what they are great at, repetitive activities or actions that require consistency and free up your people to do what they are best at, being creative and solving hard Work towards the strengths of Focus on Intelligent This seems easy enough at the beginning, but we’ve been fighting this battle for the last + years and we as an industry are just now starting to get it Every data source and every field that is available to our analysts must be mapped to a value It’s part of our jobs to make sure that data has value and that the value is articulated, measured and validated each and every Aligning to a detection framework like MITRE ATT&CK in a very specific manner is one key to determining what data must be available and why it has Key Data Sources: Network flow, alerts and session, Endpoint (OS, AV, EDR EPP), File Artifacts, Application and OS Logs, User Auth Access, Threat Intelligence, Mobile, Cloud Infrastructure and Applications, and of course enterprise context is all necessary in today’s In fact, our Survey showed that many of these were the missing pieces in the SOC that analysts would love to have available (if they didn’t already). If your SIEM doesn’t support these data types, find one that See my note about Data Engineering Most common event sources that SOC analysts wish they had avai From the VisibleRisk SOC Analyst Survey Conducted in Feb Lesson Learned : Visibility should also be instrumented in a way to help avoid vendor and or data We must create viable paths to product independence, scale, and A data engineering function that owns data from collection, through ingest and into delivery to external systems has proven highly beneficial in many They tend to leverage Kafka to handle the transport of data to analytic systems and something like Logstash or Apache Nifi to reliably deliver that information to Kafka freeing them from a single vendor and focusing them on long term success! Relentlessly Drive towards outcomes! This really should be the highlight of everything we do in the From my own experience and from my interviews there are three measurements objectives that always Healthy and maturing SOC teams relentlessly drive towards defined Understand and Drive the “Time to Detect” down . The Browser Company Contact Jobs Twitter Thanks! This is a web It’s just a frame, with some buttons and It’s our window to everything on the We love the internet, but it can be What if a browser could help us make sense of it all? Could a browser keep us focused, organized and in control? At the Browser Company , we’re building a better way to use the When we think about browsing the internet, we often ignore the browser Instead, we think about all the things we do online—the articles we read, the emails we send, the shows we The software that enables it all, the browser, is so ubiquitous that it’s Despite the ways our internet use has evolved, the browser has remained relatively While all of our other software tools are changing for the better—with more collaborative features, flexible interfaces, and powerful functionality—the browser largely still does what it did years What’s more, we blame ourselves for the browser s When our browser has an overwhelming number of tabs, we call ourselves inefficient when we get distracted online, we tell ourselves we need more discipline when we can’t find a url, we think we re Why does the browser get a free pass? That’s why we re building a new browser—we believe it could do so much more to empower We’re imagining a browser that can think as quickly as we do, take work off of our plates, and pull our creativity A browser equipped for the way we use the internet in , and foundational for how we hope to use it in the Our Team Adena Hursh Josh Nate Samir +1 Senior Front End +1 Chromium +1 Senior Generalist +1 Product Designer The five of us learned a lot from working at a handful of startups, as well as Snap, Instagram, Facebook, Amazon, and the Obama White But we don t know everything, and have a ton to Which is to say, we re eager to work with creative, kind, and passionate Especially those from diverse If all of this aligns with your values, and one of our open roles feels like it may be a fit, please say hi . Support Beyond our team, we’re lucky to be supported by our family and friends, as well as investors who played a role in some of our favorite software companies over the years (Airtable, DuckDuckGo, Github, Instagram, Slack, Stripe). While we have the financial resources to sprint at our ambitions, we’re always grateful for new perspectives and shared learnings from If you’d like to lend a hand, please send us a note . Otherwise, feel free to join our friends and family newsletter , and we promise you’ll be among the first to play with our new Thanks!

What drives success in the SOC? Skip to content Cyber Defense Operations Menu More What drives success in the SOC? Posted on April 5, April 5, by Rocky Here are five keys to success in security operations as they were derived from my interviews with SOC team leaders over the last few While this isn’t intended to be an document, I do believe it is a solid foundation for a healthy cyber defense Bonus: I’ve also listed are some of the major pitfalls that have led many organizations down a very sad and even more costly path in the hopes that others may avoid these altogether and instead focus on the strengths identified here or in the comments and conversations that this article Key Takeaway: “Healthy and maturing SOC teams relentlessly drive towards defined ” First Five “Keys” to Success: The Hire the best, then focus on growing the Invest in people over everything The right people can help you overcome flaws in technology and process if they are properly It takes talent to both attract and retain talent so don’t skimp Don’t be afraid of remote workers, with the right goals it’s very clear how everyone adds When building your team remember that diversity is key here as Hire people that ask questions by You’d be amazed by the team you can build around school teachers and police officers inquisitive and creative people can learn technology and push us to ask better questions about why we do things this We need innovative approaches, better questions, and creative It’s time to branch out past the people we know from previous lives and time to start creating the next generation to push us forw ard! Lesson learned: Having at least 3 stars on your team can help drive the right organizational dynamics and push the team across the board to be better, more collaborative and competitive in healthy Having one or two “stars” tends to drive a more negative sentiment sometimes moving towards dysfunction, whereas three or more seems to drive maturity and more healthy conversations in every Last note: Get used to remote teams, learn to manage them by having the right goals in Automate away the If it can be automated, then do If it is repeated on a daily basis, then automate If analysts are inconsistent in their delivery, then If analysts hate it, automate Basically, there is no reason for repetitive or work in the If you find yourself wanting to hire a junior person to do the tedious work – Automate SOAR can be your friend So can DevOps or any number of other tools and Lesson Learned: Technical solutions exist in many forms, but the path to success is likely not going to be adding layers of people to do the work of Having solid processed defined is the key to Let computers do what they are great at, repetitive activities or actions that require consistency and free up your people to do what they are best at, being creative and solving hard Work towards the strengths of Focus on Intelligent This seems easy enough at the beginning, but we’ve been fighting this battle for the last + years and we as an industry are just now starting to get it Every data source and every field that is available to our analysts must be mapped to a value It’s part of our jobs to make sure that data has value and that the value is articulated, measured and validated each and every Aligning to a detection framework like MITRE ATT&CK in a very specific manner is one key to determining what data must be available and why it has Key Data Sources: Network flow, alerts and session, Endpoint (OS, AV, EDR EPP), File Artifacts, Application and OS Logs, User Auth Access, Threat Intelligence, Mobile, Cloud Infrastructure and Applications, and of course enterprise context is all necessary in today’s In fact, our Survey showed that many of these were the missing pieces in the SOC that analysts would love to have available (if they didn’t already). If your SIEM doesn’t support these data types, find one that See my note about Data Engineering Most common event sources that SOC analysts wish they had avai From the VisibleRisk SOC Analyst Survey Conducted in Feb Lesson Learned : Visibility should also be instrumented in a way to help avoid vendor and or data We must create viable paths to product independence, scale, and A data engineering function that owns data from collection, through ingest and into delivery to external systems has proven highly beneficial in many They tend to leverage Kafka to handle the transport of data to analytic systems and something like Logstash or Apache Nifi to reliably deliver that information to Kafka freeing them from a single vendor and focusing them on long term success! Relentlessly Drive towards outcomes! This really should be the highlight of everything we do in the From my own experience and from my interviews there are three measurements objectives that always Healthy and maturing SOC teams relentlessly drive towards defined Understand and Drive the “Time to Detect” down . Our CRISPR gene editing: Breakthrough technology to permanently cure genetic In , a newly discovered bacterial ‘immune system’ termed CRISPR was used to edit the human CRISPR gene editing has quickly become the standard for precision genetic medicines and given hope to the millions of patients suffering from previously untreatable genetic The power of CRISPR to make a permanent change in a patient’s genetic code also requires precise control to ensure that no unintended editing takes Indeed, unintended ‘off-target’ editing could lead to severe side effects and undermine the potential of CRISPR gene editing to save and improve the lives of At Acrigen, we have developed high precision gene editing systems to dramatically improve the efficacy and safety of gene editing High precision gene The human genome contains over six billion individual In order to edit the genome at the correct location, the gene editor must exactly match the ~20 nucleotides encoded in the CRISPR Guide RNA to the target genomic Unfortunately, most systems can tolerate mismatches between the Guide and genomic DNA, leading to unintended ‘off-target’ genome Acrigen is developing high precision gene editing systems to increase the efficacy and safety of gene editing for in vivo and ex vivo Nuclease discovery We have built a robust and extensible discovery engine to identify novel We use our proprietary AcrTAIN™ bioinformatics discovery software platform to find CRISPR systems amenable for use in human We then optimize these unique enzymes by leveraging our deep expertise in protein engineering to develop highly tuned editing machines for use across in vivo and ex vivo . ErAcr protein Acrigen has developed a novel method to solve the ‘off-target’ editing Editing at unintended sites in the genome is a serious risk for any CRISPR To eliminate editing at these ‘off-target’ sites, we have developed ErAcr proteins - E ngineered R ecombinant A CR ISPR proteins - that selectively inhibit ErAcr proteins are built off of the work of Acrigen Joseph , who first discovered proteins capable of fully inhibiting Acrigen has engineered these s

are developing vaccines to protect the public from Our proprietary vaccines are based on parainfluenza virus 5 (PIV5), also known as canine parainfluenza We insert a gene encoding an antigen of interest into the PIV5 When one of our vaccine vectors is introduced to a host, it undergoes several rounds of replication, inducing robust immune responses with as few as one Robust Immune Responses In preclinical studies, we have shown that our vaccines robustly produce three forms of immunity: Cellular immunity: Cellular immunity is essential for fighting off viral While antibodies can slow down a virus, some cells will still become infected, so cellular immunity is needed to eliminate those Our vaccines regularly generate robust cytotoxic responses, a critical component of cellular Humoral immunity: A key defense against future infections, humoral immunity produces antibodies in the The efficacy of vaccines is most easily evaluated by the humoral antibody response they generate, and our vaccines produce a strong antibody response with a single Mucosal immunity: Comprised of secretory antibodies at the mucosal surface, mucosal immunity is the first line of defense against infection, blocking pathogens at their site of entry into a host (e.g. the mucosal lining of the respiratory tract). Our intranasal vaccines generate mucosal immunity because they are introduced through the nasal mucosa injected vaccines do delivery PIV5 is a respiratory virus, so our vaccines are "born intranasal". Delivered as a spray in the nose, without injections, our vaccines will facilitate broad delivery not only to pediatric and other populations, but also in parts of the world where healthcare professionals are Long track record of safety For over years, PIV5 itself has been used as part of a canine distemper (kennel cough) Dogs dosed (intranasally) with the vaccine will often sneeze, exposing veterinarians to PIV5, and they will continue to shed virus for a few days, often exposing dog owners to Many people already have antibodies against PIV5, proof that they have been exposed to the ¹ Yet despite decades of such exposure, PIV5 has never been known to cause disease in Rapid and manufacturing Because PIV5 replicates in fashion, a relatively small number of viral particles (compared with other viral vectored vaccines) is needed to make each vaccine With a relatively small bioreactor, we can theoretically produce millions of doses per month of our Conventional vaccines need manufacturing capacity measured in ,000s of liters to produce a similar number of This makes our PIV5 technology ideal for rapidly responding to emerging infectious threats, as well as for defending against existing ones ¹ Chen et al (2012), Evaluating a parainfluenza virus vaccine in a host with immunity against parainfluenza virus 5, PLOS One, 7 Like humans, dogs generate neutralizing Our software runs on machines powered by both Windows and It can be run on a local server or via the Other devices, including mobile devices, can access the software’s cloud mode through our web All versions of Windows since Windows XP are supported, as are many major Linux builds, including Ubuntu and Does the software allow for user access control and administration? Yes, our software supports distinct roles, and users must sign in (authenticate) before they begin Admins have the most control, while other roles (like the translation engineer and reviewer) have access only to the portions of the program they The admin requests and assigns translations, after which the others perform their Does your software back up clips? How do I export and distribute them? Yes, all clips (both audio and video) are saved within the Additionally, you can configure the database to store your clips to a local database at your location or to the cloud using our cloud If you’re running the software in standalone mode, you can also back up to OneDrive, Dropbox, or even a USB thumb Choose the method that you feel most comfortable Translation is a complex What part of that process does your software do?
